                     <hi rend="largeCaps">RICHARD JONES</hi> (44)</persName>, and <persName id="def4-662-18790630" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def4-662-18790630" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def4-662-18790630" type="age" value="45"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def4-662-18790630" type="surname" value="WORKMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def4-662-18790630" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EMMA WORKMAN</hi> (45)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18790630-662-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18790630-662-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18790630-662-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp>, Unlawfully conspiring together, and with others, to commit a burglary in the dwelling house of <persName id="t18790630-name-507" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-507" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-507" type="surname" value="MAUDSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-507" type="given" value="WALTER"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18790630-662-offence-1 t18790630-name-507"></join>Walter Maudsley</persName> and others, with intent to steal.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-508" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-508" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-508" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-508" type="given" value="MESSES MONTAGU"></interp>MESSES. MONTAGU WILLIAMS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CAVENDISH BENTINCKE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution;</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Defended Jones.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-509" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-509" type="surname" value="HARDING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-509" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HARDING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a prisoner awaiting sentence in the Wandsworth House of Correction—I have Known Patterson about 16 months—I first saw him in March, 1878 at Workman's house, 42, Stafford Street, High Street, Peckham, and was introduced to him by Workman at my lodgings, 14, Cork Street, Camberwell, early in May, 1878—Workman told me that Patterson was his brother-in-law—I had previously had a conversation with Workman about Maudsley's—he said, "J will use my influence with Pat, who is my brother-in-law, that you shall take Old George's place"—Old George was George Fossitt, who used to lodge at Workman's—Old George was to have taken the outside and Workman the inside part to rob Messrs. Maudsley's of two bags of money, which was taken from the Bank and deposited in a large safe, or strong room, every Friday night to pay the men's wages on Saturday morning—Workman and Patterson told me that the premises could be entered by climbing a low portico in front, about six or seven feet high, and on to the roof of the offices about four feet higher, and then, by going down some steps, or slanting roof into the yard, to enter at the back by a small circular window leading to the model-room, and then by opening one of the doors into the passage access would be got to the whole of the place—I had subsequent conversations at different tirnes with Patterson and Workman—I used to see them nearly every Sunday at my lodgings or Workman's, and sometimes in the streets—our conversation was generally about Maudsley's premises, and the robbery—before introducing Patterson Workman had mentioned the keys to me, and promised to introduce Patterson to show them to me—Patterson showed me the keys in Workman's presence and said they were the keys that would do the place where the money was kept—he said the money was kept in a small wooden cupboard in one of the strong rooms which opened into the passage with a thumb-spring—he said there were two safes, one contained petty cash and the other the wages money—he showed me two</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300210"></xptr>
               <p>keys—I had seen one of the keys being manufactured at Workman's by Fossitt from impressions taken in wax by Patterson—Patterson told me he could get impressions of any of Maudsley's keys—he said the amount of money on the premises on Friday nights varied from 1500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to 2000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and sometimes over—Workman told me be went out with Fossitt on Easter Monday to a Volunteer Review at Staines Common and Fossitt got into trouble about some housebreaking affair, and he (Workman) escaped—Patterson was introduced to me by Workman as "Mr. Baker, the party I spoke to you about to take Old George's place"—Workman called him "Pat"—that was at the Red Cap publichouse Camberwell Green—Workman said he had been and had a view of Maudsley's place and his wife went with him, and that they tried the keys and found they would do, and it was arranged I should take the outside part instead of Fossitt, and that a cabman named Gurney should have a cab waiting outside on the night of the robbery and take the money away to Patterson's house—it was to be divided into three parts, Workman and his wife taking one part, Patterson another, and myself another, but I was to give Fossitt 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 150<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. out of my share when he came out of prison—the month of November last was fixed for carrying out the scheme—I continually saw Workman and Patter<lb></lb>son up to September last—when Workman, a man named Rogers, and myself, broke into some premises in the Old Kent Road and Workman was caught. I was the outside man in that case—I kept out of the way and did not see Patterson again till the first week in November, when I went to see him—Workman was still in custody—I said to Patterson, "Has Workman said anything about this affair, or have you seen any<lb></lb>thing at Maudsley's to lead you to suppose there is any suspicion?" he said, "No; all things are going on as usual. I have not observed anything. Can you get another man to assist you in carrying out the robbery in place of Workman?" I said, "Yes, I can"—I had prior to this known Jones—he visited me at my lodgings several times—I told him that Maudsley's affair was on and proposed he should assist, and I subsequently introduced him to Patterson on Saturday night, November 16th, at the Elephant and Castle—Jones said to Patterson, "Are you still willing to carry out this affair, and have you been talking to any one else except the persons named?" meaning Fossitt and Workman; Patter<lb></lb>son said, "No. No one knows anything of it except the persons that were mentioned"—Jones asked him a few more questions about the place; if he was sure the amount of money was there, and so on, and then said, "I'll assist"—I knew at that time William Chandler and his wife, of Waterloo Street, Camberwell Park—T had previously lodged with them at 14, Cork Street, and Patterson had visited me there several times, and Workman came a great many times—on several occasions we wore all there together—Jones has been there to see me—at Workman's house Mrs. Workman was always present, taking a part in the conversation when we spoke about Maudsley's—I went down to Slough with Jones on 8th March, and we were taken into custody and convicted—I was sen<lb></lb>tenced to 12 months' imprisonment for the Slough affair—I am waiting sentence for the old Kent Road burglary.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Arthur Workman.</hi> The keys were not shown me in Stafford Street—I saw one of them, the large key, being manufactured there by Fossitt. They were shown to me at the Red Cap tavern after wards; not in your house.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300211"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi>. I am giving this information in the interests of public justice—I did not plead guilty to the Old Kent Road burglary—I gave this information after my conviction—I had previously told the detective that if I was convicted I could give them valuable inform<lb></lb>ation, and if not convicted I might not have given the information—3 convictions of felony were proved against me at the Surrey Sessions, on 6th May—I was convicted at Slough under the Prevention of Criminals Act, as an habitual criminal, and 2 previous convictions were proved against me—Mrs. Chandler was present at my conversation with Jones, bat I do not know whether she heard it—I heard her examined at the Southwark Police Court—she said she did not hear the conversation—I am not aware that any one was present at the conversation between Patterson, Jones, and myself, at the Elephant and Castle—it was at the public refreshment bar.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Emma Workman.</hi> I saw you at your house in con<lb></lb>versation with Patterson and your husband—I did not tell the police of this because you gave evidence against me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. Mrs. Workman was a witness against me in the Old Kent Road burglary case.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-510" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-510" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-510" type="surname" value="CHANDLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-510" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CHANDLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am undergoing penal servitude in Pentonville Prison—I was sentenced at the Surrey Sessions, April 9th, 1879, and had been in Wandsworth Prison from 5th November, 1877, to 3rd August, 1878—I knew Patterson seven or eight years ago—I did not know him personally, but a man named Charles Wells, of Camberwell, showed him to me—I have known Workman and his wife for some years—the witness Harding lodged in the name of Baker at 14, Cork Street, and he was lodging there in August, 1878—I have not seen Baker at my house in company with either of the other prisoners except Workman—Workman has been there hundreds of times, and visited Harding (or Baker) there a good many times—Baker and I were out housebreaking together almost daily—about the middle of August, 1878, I saw Patterson and Workman talking together at the Station Tavern, Beresford Street, Walworth Road, but I did not hear what they said—when we came away Workman said, "Do you know that party?" I said, "I have seen him before;" he said, "That's Pat, my brother-in-law. That's the party that's putting up the place in Westminster Bridge Road"—"putting up "a place means to commit a burglary Or robbery—Baker, Workman, and Dowthwaite, alias Rogers, were all out housebreaking together last year—Baker is the cleverest man—I have five or six times heard Baker and Workman, at my place, talking about Maudsley's place, Westminster Bridge Road, and concocting how to do it—I met Workman by the Crown, London Road, coming from Water<lb></lb>loo, about the middle of August—I said, "Hallo! Arthur. What's yer game?" he said, "I have just been down to see Pat." We went inside and had something to drink, and he said, "I've just been down and fetched these from him," showing me two keys, one a pipe key and the other not—I did not notice, I was a disinterested party—I said, "Is there two safes, Arthur?" and he said, "Yes, sometimes they put the money in one and sometimes in the other, so, to make sure we have had two made"—I said, "Well, if you open them with keys, Arthur, they will think it is some one about the place"—he said, "Pat will leave a few weeks before the job comes off, and they won't suspect him"—in August</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300212"></xptr>
               <p>Workman asked me to lend him 57. till November and he would give me 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for it, as he should have a fortune then—I said, "I have not got it," and offered to stand for a loan for him—the loan was for 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and we each had half—on a Monday or Tuesday night towards the end of August I went through Addington Squire, Camberwell, with Workman, and we met Patterson there, and went back to the Anchor and Hope and had something to drink, and they talked for a few minutes, and then Patterson went towards Peckham, and Workman and myself towards Camberwell—later in August I was going to the Strand with my pony and cart I have been a baker for 22 years, collecting sweepings and stale sacks from bakers, and kept a pony and cart—I was at 14, Cork Street, and offered to give Baker a ride to Pimlico—just before starting Workman came in and said, "I might at well go with you"—when we got to Westminster Bridge Road opposite a chapel near Oakley Street, he said, "Stop there, Bill; that's the place we are going to do,' pointing to a place with a coat of arms over it painted white—there was a wall about eight feet high, where they said they were going to get over to do it; and then on three or four occasions afterwards, after Workman had got into trouble, Baker had a look at the place when I gave him a ride—Baker often came in an afternoon or evening and said, "I must go round and see Patterson and his wife, and if the job comes off right I'll give Mrs. Workman 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. out of my corner, the others could give what they liked"—I knew Dowthwaite—Workman four or five times said, "Don't take any notice to Bob, as we don't want him to know, because we don't want to give him any of it; we only want to keep it between three, Patter<lb></lb>son, me, and Baker"—that was after Fossitt had got into trouble—Fossitt made the keys, and when he got into trouble Baker was introduced into the case.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Patterson.</hi> I never spoke to you in my life, but have seen you three or four times—last August I saw you once at the Station Tavern, and once at the Anchor—I had no appointment with you, and did not speak to you—Wells pointed you out as a relation of Workman's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Arthur Workman.</hi> You showed me two keys in the Crown—nobody else was with us—I know of no reason but for bravado——you have showed them to Teddy Paine, another convict—I did not expect to take any part in the burglary.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. I have known Workman since he came home from penal servitude—Fossitt was caught housebreaking last Whitsuntide twelve-months, and then Workman introduced Baker, because he knew he was a clever burglar, and but for my wife Baker would not have been here to-day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-511" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-511" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-511" type="surname" value="CHANDLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-511" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN CHANDLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am wife of William Chandler, the last witness, and live at 15, Aylesbury Street, Walworth—I formerly lived at 14, Cork Street—Harding lodged there—I knew him as Baker—my husband was then a prisoner for nine months—Patterson has been at my house with Workman and wife, and by himself—he generally came on Sundays alone to see Baker—he came once with Workman to see my husband before he went away, and once with Baker when he was away—I remember him coming one Sunday, and asking if Baker was at home—I said, "No, he is out; have you a message to leave?"—he said, "No, I will see him in the week"—he left, and I saw no more of him—I had heard Workman and Baker talking together—Workman never told me anything about a job he had in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300213"></xptr>
               <p>November, but I heard what he said to Baker—that was before my husband returned, between April, when Fossitt fell, up to August—Workman said, "I don't know what I shall do now Old George has fell. I have a very good job in hand; if I give it to you will you give Old George half your corner when he comes home?"—he said, "Oh, yes"—after August I heard Workman say to my husband, "I can't think why Baker keeps away from our house, as we have a very good job in hand in November at Mr. Maudsley's, with Patterson"—I have seen Dowthwaite at our house—I have seen wax of a slatish colour in Workman's possession, and saw the impression of a key, which they said was a safe key—I have seen Davis, the other prisoner, twice—he came to see Baker about twice in my parlour, but I was not in the room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Patterson.</hi> I was taken into custody with my husband on the same charge, and on a second charge of receiving stolen property in my husband's absence—I was in prison some time, and was acquitted—my husband was convicted—you came once to my house, and saw me alone with my child.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Arthur Workman.</hi> No one else but myself was present when you had the conversation with Baker in my back room—I cannot tell what day of the week it was—it was quite 9 months ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi>. I heard nothing that was said.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-512" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-512" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-512" type="surname" value="ROGERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-512" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT ROGERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I sometimes go by the name of Dowthwaite—I was convicted with Workman at the Surrey Sessions for housebreaking on 15th October, 1878, and am now undergoing penal servitude at Penton<lb></lb>ville—I know George Fossitt as a lodger of Workman's, and Patterson as Workman's brother-in-law—I have had conversations with Fossitt about a burglary in Westminster Bridge Road, but he did not mention Maudsley's—at the end of January, 1878, he showed me a blank key, and told me that he and Workman had a good job on—I have heard Fossitt and Work man talking the matter over together—they said the key was made at Workman's house and took two days to make, and it fitted the safe it was intended to open—Fossitt told me that there was about 2,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in the safe—I told him I should not let that die a natural death, and he said, "I should think not; it's something worth attending to"—I called on him frequently at Workman's house, and Mrs. Workman generally opened the door, and was present at several conversations—on Whit Sunday Workman and his wife and Patterson were in the parlour—as Patterson left to go home to dinner he said to the Workmans, "Now, remember your promise; for if you miss this chance of seeing it you won't get another '—I went again on the Wednesday, and I talked about being caught in the rain on Whit-Monday, and Workman said they were in the same predicament coming from Westminster Bridge—I said, "Well, did you see what you went to see?" he said—"We saw it all"—I said, "You know where to go and put your hand on it now?" and he said, "Yes, I can find it blindfolded"—after that he got a situation for the purpose of doing it, and I went round to his house on a Tuesday morning when he had been there a little over a week, and Mrs. Workman said he had been in on the Sunday and wanted to see me very particularly—she said, "There's something up there for you," pointing to a picture on the wall, and I found two pieces of wax at the top of the frame—she said, "You are to make them, and I am to take them down to-morrow"—I said, "I can't make keys from these; they</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300214"></xptr>
               <p>arc damaged; you had better take the wax down again to-morrow, and let him take them afresh"—she went down on Wednesday, and I called on Thursday, and again on Friday morning—Workman lost his situation at Aldershot after being there 9 or 10 days—I made another key for another safe job we had on—Mrs. Workman showed it to Patterson in my presence—she said she liked to handle those sort of things, and Patterson said it was like a key that fitted theirs, but neater made—Workman told me Fossitt had got three months—I said, "He won't be in time to do the affair you have on," Maudsley's—He said, "We'll put Baker into it"—I said, "You don't mean to push Old George out of it altogether?"—he said, "No; we have arranged to allow him so much out of each of our corners; I dare say it will be about a cent."—that is 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—six of us proposed to go to Staines on Easter Monday, but only Fossitt and Workman went, and Fossitt fell, and Workman got away—"fell" means he was caught.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Arthur Workman.</hi> Only Mrs. Workman was present when she showed me the impressions of the cash box keys you left to be given to me to make, and she only was present when you told me you had been to the place and could find it blindfolded—the police came to see me at Pentonville, and said they had heard I knew something about the intended burglary, and asked me if I would give evidence in this case; I asked if I should get any benefit, and they said they could not promise anything or hold out any inducement.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-513" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-513" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-513" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-513" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, at 1, Garden Row, London Road—in May last I was sent to Wandsworth Gaol for a month—Workman was in the next cell, and spoke to me on many occasions while going to chapel or out in the exercise ground—he asked me to take a message to a Mrs. Clark, 104, Warner Road, when I got out, and to tell her the "Coppers," Hunt and Chamberlain, had been, and he was sorry "Pat" had "fell;" they wanted him (Workman) to come up and give evidence against Pat, but he told them he knew nothing about it, and they went away very cross—Workman asked me to go his wife, 14, Bath Place, Addington Square, Camherwell, and tell her the Coppers had been about Maudsley's job, and she must keep her "guts" what she knew about it, and that he had told the Coppers he had been with her to Maudsley's 18 months ago to look at the models while the clerks were in the country.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Arthur Workman.</hi> I have been convicted of felony once before—your wife was not at Bath Place, and I went to her at Cam<lb></lb>berwell Workhouse as you told me, but did not give her the message; she said, "Come down to-night"—I gave Mrs. Clark the message—I went to Carter Street and gave information that you had given me a message to your wife that she was not to give information to the police if they came that you had been to Maudsley's to see the keys—a man stopped me and said I should be well paid if I did not give information against you—the police summoned me to come here—I do not know if I shall be paid as a witness—I was fetched to the police-court.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Emma Workman.</hi> I told you at Camberwell I had a message from your husband, and he was very sorry Pat had fell—I did not go down at night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> The man I met in the street had a black moustache, and was with Mrs. Workman—he touched me on the shoulder and said, "You have just come out of 'stir,' haven't you?"—I said "Yes"—and he said,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300215"></xptr>
               <p>"What did he say to you?"—I took him up the next street and told him, and he said, "If you don't go and give information you will get well paid for it"—this was about 5.30 or 5.45.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-514" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-514" type="surname" value="HUNT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-514" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>DANIEL HUNT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Detective-Inspecter P.</hi>). I and Chamberlain had Work<lb></lb>man in custody last September—I know his wife and Rogers, alias Dowthwaite—Workman made certain communications to me before his conviction, and subsequently his wife also made certain communications to me—I was at Slough on 26th March, when Davis and Harding were tried and convicted—Harding, alias Biker, made a statement to me before his conviction, and at three interviews after his conviction, in consequence of which I saw Mrs. Chandler—I obtained an order from the Home Secretary and saw William Chandler, and made certain inquiries, and then reported to Scotland Yard, and this prosecution was instituted—I obtained an order to see Workman, and saw him at Wandsworth on 24th May, and told him the object of my visit, and that Patterson was in custody with others on this charge, and said, "Now do you know anything about the case?"—he said, "No; I can have nothing to say in the case"—I said, "Do you know Patterson?"—he said, "Yes; I have known him about 16 years"—I said, "We are in possession of the whole facts of the case. We know that you can give evidence in this case if you like. Will you do it?"—he said, "No; I can have nothing to do with that job; I can't give evidence against my brother-in-law. Besides that, it was nearly two years ago it was talked about?—I said, "Do you recollect being in a certain public-house when the keys were shown to Baker by Patterson in your presence?"—he said, "Yes, I recollect being in a public-house with Patterson and Baker at the Father Red Cap, Camber well Green, one Sunday evening last May (1876), but Patterson did not show Baker the keys. In fact, I do net think Baker ever saw them. I went with my wife once about fifteen months ago, and had a look ever the place referring to Maudsley's. Patterson showed us over the premises and showed us the models"—he declined to give further testimony—on 23rd May with Inspector Chamberlain I saw Mrs. Workman at the Orange Tree Beerhouse, Avill Street, camberwell—I said, "Patterson is in custody charged with others conspiring to commit a burglary at Messrs. Maudsley's and it is said you have been there and know all about it; will you tell us what you know I"—she said, "No. I shall have nothing at all to do with it. I know nothing about it; I have heard it was intended to break in; but that was sometime ago"—I said, "Well, if you decline to give the necessary infor<lb></lb>mation there are plenty others who can," mentioning Chandler and his wile—she said, "Mrs. Chandler, let her say what she likes. She is only wild she didn't have the job to climb blooming well herself"—I asked her if I should see her again in the evening, and she said "Yes, come alone. See me at 7 o'clock at my house"—I called there about 6.30, and she was not at home—I saw her about 7 with Mrs. Patterson, the prisoner's wife, leaving the house, and after she had left Mrs. Patterson I spoke to her again about giving me information and told her I was going to see her husband—she said, "I'll wait and see what Arthur does"—she said she could not give in<lb></lb>formation as she had not been paid for the last job—she had given evidence in Harding's case—she said, if her husband gave evidence she would do the same—she afterwards said, "As Patterson has found me and ray children food and shelter for two months after Arthur was put away, I cannot find it in my</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300216"></xptr>
               <p>heart to hurt him. I know the affair was arranged and would have come off had it been kept quiet. I think it is nearly two years ago it was first talked about. I went with my husband once into Mr. Maudsley's place. We went to see the models. Patterson showed us over the premises. We had some ale there—I know some keys were made, two lots, and I believe that Baker had them with him when he was taken at Slough As the job did not come off you can do nothing with it. You can do nothing with Patterson—Patterson and Baker did come to my house several times—I intended to wait until the job was done, and if a reward was offered, to give informa<lb></lb>tion—lid you expect to find the keys when you reached Patterson's house?" I said "Yes, I suppose they did. I was not there myself." She said, "Ah! clever men never keep those things in their own houses"—I said, well! if the affair had taken place she would not have got so much as she thought, perhaps. She said, "If it had been done at the right time, there would have been a good lot there, and they did not mean to do it except when there was plenty there. Sometimes it's more than at others. I will think the matter over, and perhaps I'll tell you more about it. I'll wait and see what Arthur does."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Arthur Workman.</hi> This conversation was on the evening of the 23rd May, the day preceding that on which I saw you at Wandsworth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Emma Workman.</hi> I did not ask you to go to Mr. Wontner—as a fact he would not be engaged in the case then—when I saw you at the Orange Tree I asked you if you had reconsidered your determination, and whether you would become a witness, and you declined—I was then unaware what steps would be taken—you asked me if the keys were in the bag found on Baker at Slough—I said, "No, there were no keys of that description"—I said, "There is a sovereign in my pocket for you"—that had no reference to this case—you said, "Those keys, if we could find them, would be worth a thousand pounds," and asked me how much I would give for them—I did not say, "I will give you 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for them."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-515" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-515" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-515" type="surname" value="CHAMBERLAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-515" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CHAMBERLAIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Inspector L</hi>). I have been present and have heard Hunt's statements as to these conversations, and they are sub<lb></lb>stantially correct—I took Patterson in custody on the 22nd May, in Kennington Road—I said, "I am a police officer, and hold a warrant for your apprehension for being concerned with others in conspiring to break into your master's premises, Maudsley's"—he said, "I know nothing about it; who are the others?"—I said, "A man named Davis or Jones, and another named Harding, who were taken in custody at Slough some weeks ago for robbery"—Mrs. Workman made a statement to me after she was in custody—she said, "Mr. Chamberlain, this is a very bad job"—I said, "Yes, it is"—she said, "I wish I had told you and Mr. Hunt the truth the other night when I saw you at the Orange Tree"—I said, "Why didn't you?"—she said, "I hardly knew what to say about it then, I have been in the place (<hi rend="italic">meaning Maudsley's</hi>) with my husband. Patterson took him and me in. They didn't allow me to go over the place with them. They shut me in a room whilst they went and done what they wanted"—I said, "Why did they do that?"—she said, "Patterson was afraid that the persons in the next house might see a woman in the house, which would cause some suspicion."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-516" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-516" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-516" type="surname" value="TRIMME"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-516" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN TRIMME</persName>
                  </hi>. I am manager to Messrs. Maudsley—I have been in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300217"></xptr>
               <p>Court and heard Harding's description of the premises and it is perfectly correct—we were in the habit of paying the men on Saturday—the money was obtained from the Bank on Friday morning, and kept in safes in the room as described by Harding, in iron safes in a wooden locker—the wages are sometimes as high as 2,500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a week.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Patterson.</hi> The amount last Friday was consider<lb></lb>ably over 1,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—it ranged from 800<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to 2,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., according to the number of men—we have had nearly 2,000 men during the last 12 months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-517" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-517" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-517" type="surname" value="MAUDSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-517" type="given" value="WALTER HENRY"></interp>WALTER HENRY MAUDSLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a member of the firm of Maudsley and Co., Engineers—I have heard our premises described to-day and that description is accurate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Patterson.</hi> You have been in our employ about four and a half years—I believe we received a good character with you, but Mr. Trimme can speak to that—you have been during the last three years in the office and I have seen you almost daily and have never seen anything in your conduct to lead me to suspect you were connected with such men as the other prisoners—you used to fetch the money on Fridays, you and another messenger together, in bags from the Bank—I cannot say if you had an opportunity of seeing the cheque drawn every Friday—there are two cheques drawn, the larger amount on Friday and the other on Saturday morning—it has not been so low as 400<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I cannot speak as to the number of men we had.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-eximined.</hi> I did not know when we took Patterson into our service that he had been sentenced to penal servitude—I have since ascertained it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the Prisoner.</hi> I believe that was 15 years ago—I have seen the papers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-518" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-518" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-518" type="surname" value="CHAMBERLAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-518" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CHAMBERLAIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Re-examined</hi>). I had a conversation with Patterson when he was taken with Workman—he said, "It was through him partly that I got into trouble before—it is some years ago now since I had the five years"—he volunteered the statement—I had these papers with me and showed him his photograph (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) and he said, "Yes, it's quite right" (<hi rend="italic">certificate produced</hi>)—he had a ticket of leave and failed to report himself, and ought to have been apprehended.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by Patterson.</hi> You freely acknowledged this, and told me the date, and where you had been—you gave me three written characters from where you had been employed—you had been at one place nine months; at another place they could not find you in their books, and at Smith and Taylor's, Pimlico, they admitted that you were employed there as a labourer, but did not know how long.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Patterson produced a written defence, denying the charge, and assenting that the witnesses' statements were wicked fabrications.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Arthur Workman, in his defence, stated that the police had not told the truth, and had been working the case up solely on the letter they had received from Harding, and that Harding's statement at the Police Court was a tissue of falsehoods, and that there was no evidence to support that of the convicts. He also stated that during the last thirty years he had been occupied as a grocer, a photographer, and as a police-constable, and was never a housebreaker, except once with Rogers, when in great poverty. Emma Workman, in her defence, stated that she knew nothing of the charge; that she never saw the keys, that she had been annoyed by the police every time her husband got into trouble, and that the evidence was perfectly false.</hi>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300218"></xptr>
